India’s 6-Month Borrowing Costs Rise at T-Bill Auction

-- B y   J e a n e t t e   R o d r i g u e s
-- 
2011-09-28T09:18:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-28/india-s-6-month-borrowing-costs-rise-at-t-bill-auction.html
India ’s six-month borrowing costs
rose and three-month costs were unchanged. The government raised
100 billion rupees selling treasury bills at a weekly auction,
the central bank said.  The government sold 70 billion rupees of 91-day bills at a
minimum price of 97.94 rupees per 100 rupee face amount, or a
maximum yield of 8.4364 percent, the Reserve Bank of India said
in an e-mailed statement today, unchanged from an auction on
Aug. 21. It also auctioned 30 billion rupees of 182-day bills at
a cut-off price of 95.95 rupees, or a yield of 8.4651 percent,
higher than 8.3998 percent on Aug. 14.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jeanette Rodrigues in Mumbai at 
